T1  - The optimal ability-education mix and the misallocation of resources within education magnitude for developing countries
AU  - Piñera, Sebastian
AU  - Selowsky, Marcelo
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 8
IS  - 1
SP  - 111
EP  - 131
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(81)90048-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387881900481
AB  - The central notion of this paper is the hypothesis of factor complementarity between preschool ability and schooling in determining labor productivity. Hence, an optimal allocation of existing educational resources across students with different abilities ought to induce a positive and perfect correlation between ability and schooling. A system where schooling is determined by factors other than ability (i.e., the selection process of that system) induces a misallocation of present resources in education. An analytical framework is specified to derive magnitudes of the economic cost of this misallocation. It is shown that these values are substantial when compared to the welfare cost of other types of resource misallocation in developing countries.
