T1  - Foreign ownership, market structure and industrial performance: Brazil's electrical industry
AU  - Newfarmer, Richard S.
AU  - Marsh, Lawrence C.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 8
IS  - 1
SP  - 47
EP  - 75
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(81)90045-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387881900456
AB  - Using an industrial organization approach, this article tests the hypothesis that the ownership of firms exerts an independent influence on industrial performance. We compare the behavior of foreign and domestic firms in Brazil's electrical industry in four areas: the association of firms with particular types of domestic market structures, their technology, their trade conduct, and their profitability. Regression analysis shows that TNCs tend to produce in tightly organized, differentiated oligopolies; they generally employ a more capital-intensive technology; they import more per unit of sales, but do not necessarily export more; finally, reported earnings of TNCs are found not to be any higher than domestic firms, but reported profits of all firms are positively related to the level of industrial concentration and product differentiation, markets which tend to be the domain of TNCs rather than domestic enterprises. It is concluded that ownership is a strong variable of market structure in Brazil's electrical industry and that the systematic effect of foreign ownership on industrial performance is not always helpful in attaining development objectives.
