T1  - Total factor productivity, non-neutral technical change and economic growth: A parametric study of a developing economy
AU  - Levy, Victor
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 8
IS  - 1
SP  - 93
EP  - 109
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(81)90047-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438788190047X
AB  - The traditional approach to productivity analysis relies on the assumptions of constant return to scale, neutral technical change and payments to factors according to their marginal productivity. Intuitively one feels that such simplifications might give biased results, specifically in a planned developing economy where the last assumption is most likely violated. This study develops a parametric approach to the analysis of total and specific factor productivity, which does not rely on the above assumptions and applies it to the industrial sector on Iraq. We measure the biases in the direction of technical change and analyze their implications for employment problems in LDC's.
